QUEUE USING ARRAY
AIM
To implement a Queue using Array and perform Insert (Enqueue), Delete (Dequeue) and Display operations.
THEORY
A Queue is a linear data structure that follows the principle FIFO (First In First Out).
Insertion of elements takes place at the rear end, and deletion of elements takes place at the front end.
Queue Operations
Insert (Enqueue) – Adds an element at the rear.
Delete (Dequeue) – Removes an element from the front.
Display – Displays all elements of the queue.
Queue Conditions
Overflow: When rear == MAX - 1
Underflow: When front == -1 or front > rear
ALGORITHM
Algorithm for INSERT (Enqueue)
Start
If rear == MAX - 1, print Queue Overflow
Else
If front == -1, set front = 0
Increment rear
Insert element at queue[rear]
Stop
Algorithm for DELETE (Dequeue)
Start
If front == -1 OR front > rear, print Queue Underflow
Else
Print element at queue[front]
Increment front
Stop
Algorithm for DISPLAY
Start
If front == -1 OR front > rear, print Queue is empty
Else
Display elements from front to rear
Stop
PROGRAM
Copy code
C
#include <stdio.h>
#define MAX 5

int queue[MAX];
int front = -1;
int rear = -1;

void insert(int x) {
    if (rear == MAX - 1) {
        printf("Queue Overflow\n");
    } else {
        if (front == -1)
            front = 0;
        rear++;
        queue[rear] = x;
    }
}

void delete() {
    if (front == -1 || front > rear) {
        printf("Queue Underflow\n");
    } else {
        printf("Deleted element: %d\n", queue[front]);
        front++;
    }
}

void display() {
    int i;
    if (front == -1 || front > rear) {
        printf("Queue is empty\n");
    } else {
        printf("Queue elements:\n");
        for (i = front; i <= rear; i++) {
            printf("%d ", queue[i]);
        }
        printf("\n");
    }
}

int main() {
    insert(10);
    insert(20);
    insert(30);

    delete();
    display();

    return 0;
}
OUTPUT
Copy code

Deleted element: 10
Queue elements:
20 30
